Caecilius Statius (24, 2 5, 36), a freedman of Insubrian birth, wh0‚ like his contemporary Plautus, translated and worked over the comedies of Menander and other Greek writers, Of his plays only fragments are extant, but Cicero (de Opt. Carvilius Maximus, Sp. (11), cos, 13.c. 234, and, with Fabius Maxi- mus Cunctator, 13.C. 228. He is noted chiefly for his proposition, after the battle of Cannae, to fill up the depleted ranks of the Roman sena- tors by choosing two representatives from each Latin community (Liv. 23, 22, 5). He was a plebeian and did not support his colleague Maximus ⁴ in his opposition to the democratic measure of Flaminius in regard to the assignment of Gallie and Picene lands.

Cineas (43), a pupil of DemostheneS, whom Pyrrhus sent as ambas- sador to Rome after his first victory, over Laevinus, 13.c. 280. His proposals¹ for peace were successfully opposed by Appius Claudius Caecus. Two years later was the Roman embassy of Fabricius and others to Pyrrhus, on which occasion Cineas returned the hospitality which he had experienced in Rome. Cineas’ usual success as ambas- sador led Pyrrhus to say that he had won more cities by words than he himself had by weapons (Plut. Pyrrhus, 14).
